PiperOrigin-RevId: 387145375
Change-Id: Ia6bfa49da4fb62ac22b53612aad88124e9ae43bc","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sthagen/tensorflow/commits/2f55a91c4e9e57ac5649bf54d99da8ae96de9cb5"},{"sha":"86af5fd93fc70db185405d2d130850d5d20f7bb3","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[PJRT] Tweak transpose loop ordering and block size selection heuristic.

* Move the code that chooses the loop ordering after the code that chooses a block size.
* When computing the stride of a block dimension, multiply it by the block size. Previously we weren't doing this, which meant we incorrectly though that loops that iterated over blocks had small strides.
* Use `min(a_stride * penalty, b_stride)` instead of `a_stride * penalty + b_stride` as the loop heuristic. If a dimension has a small stride in one array but an enormous stride in another, we probably care more about keeping the small strided accesses together. Empirically this seems to improve benchmarks.
* Tweak block size selection heuristic. Don't use an inner_block_size smaller than the smallest vectorized kernel we have. Also, prefer to visit the entirety of the dimension in a single outer_block if it's small enough.

[{"sha":"6515f376adc6b2271446f08aa17717502766bdf6","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"addrs: Factor out MoveEndpointInModule module prefix matching

All of our MoveDestination methods have the common problem of deciding
whether the receiver is even potentially in the scope of a particular
MoveEndpointInModule, which requires that the receiver belong to an
instance of the module where the move statement was found.

Previously we had this logic inline in all three cases, but now we'll
factor it out into a shared helper function.

At first it seemed like there ought to be more factoring possible for
the AbsResource vs. AbsResourceInstance implementations, since textually
they look very similar, but in practice they only look similar because
those two types have a lot of method names in common, but the Go compiler
sees them as completely distinct and thus we must write the same logic
out twice. I did try some further refactoring to address that but it
made the resulting code significantly more complicated and, by my
judgement, harder to follow. Consequently I decided that a little
duplication was okay and warranted here because this logic is already
quite fiddly to read through and isn't likely to change significantly once
released (due to backward-compatibility promises).","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/6515f376adc6b2271446f08aa17717502766bdf6"}]

Improves transposes such as f32[1, 1024, 1]{2, 1, 0} -> f32[1, 1024, 1]{1, 2, 0}T(2, 128). The loop simplification cannot remove the degenerate second-minor `1` dimension and it was ending up innermost. Some ops don't follow the common semantics (i.e., empty or anonymous
`shared_name` guaranteeing unique allocated resources) so we can't utilize those
semantics in resource alias analysis. See e.g. `FusedResizeAndPadConvFunctor`.
Also added warning about resource-allocating ops that are treated conservatively
in resource alias analysis.

Change-Id: Idd682d6790f6683718afc1cec3f045ab4ebb9f6f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sthagen/tensorflow/commits/f6194ac06e7dc5155e0c78fda13a01c5cd092582"},{"sha":"604489d05f36647dd8815452ce22b295881f834b","author":{"name":"Peng Wang","email":"b55f18ff6423501a9509f40f9539fd4a14e4c9f9@google.com"},"message":"Removes the `SetIsStateful` mark on op `StatelessRandomGetKeyCounter` (the mark causes problems in tf.data iterator checkpointing).

Theoretically the op's output is device-dependent so it's kind of "stateful", but the V2 stateless RNG ops are also device-dependent (when alg=AUTO_SELECT) and not marked as stateful. We are using the same criterion here.

Note that removing the "stateful" mark won't cause the op to be constant-folded away (like `StatelessRandomGetAlg`).

[{"sha":"fa5a2a6fa8927abd06113f4e6ac3a9b8bd7cd42a","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"addrs: MoveDestination for AbsResourceInstance-based move endpoints

Previously our MoveDestination methods only honored move statements whose
endpoints were module calls, module instances, or resources.

Now we'll additionally handle when the endpoints are individual resource
instances. This situation only applies to
AbsResourceInstance.MoveDestination because no other objects can be
contained inside of a resource instance.

This completes all of the MoveDestination cases for all supported move
statement types and moveable object types.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/fa5a2a6fa8927abd06113f4e6ac3a9b8bd7cd42a"}]

[{"sha":"ac72971cc6fbbfe4df7e67a8347ef1b6ab63b5fd","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[PJRT] Tweak the logic that orders the dimensions of A to handle degenerate minor dimensions better.

Improves transposes such as f32[1, 1024, 1]{2, 1, 0} -> f32[1, 1024, 1]{1, 2, 0}T(2, 128). The loop simplification cannot remove the degenerate second-minor `1` dimension and it was ending up innermost. But there's no reason why we can't treat the 1024 dimension as innermost in the input, and then this becomes a decently-sized memcpy() kernel.

[{"sha":"5faa86a4d711027e66d6464b02b8f7612d949c7b","author":{"name":"Christian Sigg","email":"bf0bb771be8a27677291ada19f594af5450440c6@google.com"},"message":"Don't mark XLA GPU targets as compatible_with cloud.

XLA GPU depends on CUDA libraries which are not compatible, and without them the targets don't do anything useful (even if they build fine). This also avoids having to mark TFRT GPU targets (that XLA GPU wants to depend on) as compatible_with cloud.

Explicitly mark a few targets as compatible_with cloud, because the XLA CPU backend depends on them.

Change-Id: Idd682d6790f6683718afc1cec3f045ab4ebb9f6f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/f6194ac06e7dc5155e0c78fda13a01c5cd092582"},{"sha":"604489d05f36647dd8815452ce22b295881f834b","author":{"name":"Peng Wang","email":"b55f18ff6423501a9509f40f9539fd4a14e4c9f9@google.com"},"message":"Removes the `SetIsStateful` mark on op `StatelessRandomGetKeyCounter` (the mark causes problems in tf.data iterator checkpointing).

Theoretically the op's output is device-dependent so it's kind of "stateful", but the V2 stateless RNG ops are also device-dependent (when alg=AUTO_SELECT) and not marked as stateful. We are using the same criterion here.

Note that removing the "stateful" mark won't cause the op to be constant-folded away (like `StatelessRandomGetAlg`).

[{"sha":"b8f9cc0699727132e86576d8c088d66eaf3d4c40","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"seccomp.Syscall: embed runtime-spec Syscall type

This makes the type better reflect the difference with the "runtime" profile;
our local type is used to generate a runtime-spec seccomp profile and extends
the runtime-spec type with additional fields; adding a "Name" field for backward
compatibility with older JSON representations, additional "Comment" metadata,
and conditional rules ("Includes", "Excludes") used during generation to adjust
the profile based on the container (capabilities) and host's (architecture, kernel)
configuration.

This change introduces one change in the type; the "runtime-spec" type uses a
`[]LinuxSeccompArg` for the `Args` field, whereas the local type used pointers;
`[]*LinuxSeccompArg`.

In addition, the runtime-spec Syscall type brings a new `ErrnoRet` field, allowing
the profile to specify the errno code returned for the syscall, which allows

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Legalize mhlo.not to TFLogicalNotOp

In fact, there was a pattern in dealing with mhlo.not. However, that operation included a mistake. It required the operand to be TF_IntOrFpTensor and it also demanded SameOperandsAndResultType. Under this circumstance, the pattern became a vacuous one as the result type of NotOp must be Bool and the input operand is IntOrFp. I fixed this bug by simply replacing TF_IntOrFpTensor with TF_BoolTensor in the definition of the pattern.

Change-Id: Idd682d6790f6683718afc1cec3f045ab4ebb9f6f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sloppyjuicy/tensorflow/commits/f6194ac06e7dc5155e0c78fda13a01c5cd092582"},{"sha":"604489d05f36647dd8815452ce22b295881f834b","author":{"name":"Peng Wang","email":"b55f18ff6423501a9509f40f9539fd4a14e4c9f9@google.com"},"message":"Removes the `SetIsStateful` mark on op `StatelessRandomGetKeyCounter` (the mark causes problems in tf.data iterator checkpointing).

Theoretically the op's output is device-dependent so it's kind of "stateful", but the V2 stateless RNG ops are also device-dependent (when alg=AUTO_SELECT) and not marked as stateful. We are using the same criterion here.

Note that removing the "stateful" mark won't cause the op to be constant-folded away (like `StatelessRandomGetAlg`).

[{"sha":"9852ad6ebead5e2fa286c07f45191a742d3884a4","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"addrs: ModuleInstance.ChildCall method

This allows us to concisely construct AbsModuleCall address values by
method chaining from module instance addresses.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/9852ad6ebead5e2fa286c07f45191a742d3884a4"},{"sha":"6d5ee1cb0ce19b405c6bdd79342906ee34f697df","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"instances: Expander.AllInstances

In order to precisely implement the validation rules for "moved"
statements we need to be able to test whether particular instances were
declared in the configuration.

The instance expander is the source of record for which instances we
decided while creating a plan, but it's API is far more involved than what
our validation rules need, so this new AllInstances method returns a
wrapper object with a more straightforward API that provides read-only
access to just the question of whether particular instances got registered
in the expander already.

This API covers all three of the kinds of objects that move statements can
refer to. It includes module calls and resources, even though they aren't
_themselves_ "instances" in the sense we usually mean, because the module
instance addresses they are contained within _are_ instances and so we
need to take their dynamic instance keys into account when answering these
queries.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/6d5ee1cb0ce19b405c6bdd79342906ee34f697df"}]

[{"sha":"2c792ac08fa1e777d259a8da8a52382430e509f8","author":{"name":"George Karpenkov","email":"bbf3fb1cea1ba929a95f09c9e20513124012c8d3@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Serialize alias_passthrough_params property to HLO IR

Currently, the property is not serialized, which leads to inability to
reproduce bugs and performance regressions just from the IR, as the
alias_passthrough_params property affects the execution semantics.

The resulting modules are executable with run_hlo_module, but currently they
will miscompare against the reference implementation for the aliased params
(which still allows to compare other parameters, and check performance and
absence of crashes).

Added an option `awslogs-create-stream` to allow skipping log stream
creation for awslogs log driver. The default value is still true to
keep the behavior be consistent with before.

Signed-off-by: Xia Wu <xwumzn@amazon.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kinvolk/moby/commits/d10046f228e4152b12bb6ce7db0008f227b95790"},{"sha":"00a4f67ddf78883bb6e891ec3943de08564e209d","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Reduce TestClientWithRequestTimeout flakiness

The test sometimes failed because no error was returned:

    === Failed
    === FAIL: pkg/plugins TestClientWithRequestTimeout (0.00s)
         client_test.go:254: assertion failed: expected an error, got nil: expected error

Possibly caused by a race condition, as the sleep was just 1 ms longer than the timeout;
this patch is increasing the sleep in the response to try to reduce flakiness.

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kinvolk/moby/commits/00a4f67ddf78883bb6e891ec3943de08564e209d"},{"sha":"f3d08d59aa402444a311701dc231f4a1e83440df","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"volume/mounts: move some code to correct location, and minor linting/formatting

Signed-off-by: Roman Volosatovs <roman.volosatovs@docker.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kinvolk/moby/commits/cdd04a94bcbd33edac73bb945f57c2e21fed7641"},{"sha":"2837fba75f5ee7e57c167af4e70569adaf59377a","author":{"name":"Roman Volosatovs","email":"de37379432a0923e9d62232e7753800cfd82d951@docker.com"},"message":"libnetwork: ensure all nodes are available in tests

`github.com/hashicorp/memberlist` update caused `TestNetworkDBCRUDTableEntries`
to occasionally fail, because the test would try to check whether an entry
write is propagated to all nodes, but it would not wait for all nodes to
be available before performing the write.
It could be that the failure is caused simply by improved performance of
the dependency - it could also be that some connectivity guarantee the
test depended on is not provided by the dependency anymore.
The same fix is applied to `TestNetworkDBNodeJoinLeaveIteration` due to
same issue.

Signed-off-by: Roman Volosatovs <roman.volosatovs@docker.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kinvolk/moby/commits/2837fba75f5ee7e57c167af4e70569adaf59377a"},{"sha":"bf9c76f0a8ff296c71d32bb46c1ea03f8ec1dd14","author":{"name":"Roman Volosatovs","email":"de37379432a0923e9d62232e7753800cfd82d951@docker.com"},"message":"API, daemon/images: add ImageListOptions and pass context

[{"sha":"6397c035dac774b69689d0227b34752b71608ba0","author":{"name":"Daniel Ellis","email":"debc5fc5255503ceceb6184687cd26898e40e8ac@google.com"},"message":"Fix segmentation fault in shape inference logic.

When running shape functions, some functions (such as `MutableHashTableShape`)
produce extra output information in the form of a `ShapeAndType` struct.  The
shapes embedded in this struct are owned by an inference context that is
cleaned up almost immediately; if the upstream code attempts to access this
shape information, it can trigger a segfault.

`ShapeRefiner` is mitigating this for normal output shapes by cloning them
(and thus putting the newly created shape under ownership of an inference
context that will not die), but we were not doing the same for shapes and
types.  This commit fixes that by doing similar logic on output shapes and
types.

Srivastava","email":"904a07f5d5a3adde1e4d458a4465bbe1e0df36dc@polymagelabs.com"},"message":"[MLIR][TF] Canonicalize tf.DivNoNan and tf.MulNoNan

Added and used a template to canonicalize tf.DivNoNan and tf.MulNoNan.
When the divisor/multiplier of tf.DivNoNan/tf.MulNoNan, respectively is
a constant with all the elements in its tensor (with float/complex type)
being zero, tf.DivNoNan/tf.MulNoNan is replaced with its
divisor/multiplier, respectively. Further, when the divisor/multiplier
of tf.DivNoNan/tf.MulNoNan, respectively is a constant with all the
elements in its tensor (with float/complex type) being non-zero,
tf.DivNoNan/tf.MulNoNan is replaced with tf.Div/tf.Mul, respectively.
Relevant test cases are added as well.

Previously our MoveDestination methods only honored move statements whose
endpoints were module calls or module instances.

Now we'll additionally handle when the endpoints are whole resource
addresses. This includes both renaming resource blocks and moving resource
blocks into or out of child modules.

Previously our MoveDestination methods only honored move statements whose
endpoints were module calls, module instances, or resources.

Now we'll additionally handle when the endpoints are individual resource
instances. This situation only applies to
AbsResourceInstance.MoveDestination because no other objects can be
contained inside of a resource instance.

This completes all of the MoveDestination cases for all supported move
statement types and moveable object types.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vdavalon01/terraform/commits/45d16b4a2b6497b748127160f0bd15ed07a2e9cb"},{"sha":"5a6d11e37533c7ca607a706a64fc6f1f079fdffa","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"addrs: Factor out MoveEndpointInModule module prefix matching

All of our MoveDestination methods have the common problem of deciding
whether the receiver is even potentially in the scope of a particular
MoveEndpointInModule, which requires that the receiver belong to an
instance of the module where the move statement was found.

Previously we had this logic inline in all three cases, but now we'll
factor it out into a shared helper function.

At first it seemed like there ought to be more factoring possible for
the AbsResource vs. AbsResourceInstance implementations, since textually
they look very similar, but in practice they only look similar because
those two types have a lot of method names in common, but the Go compiler
sees them as completely distinct and thus we must write the same logic
out twice. I did try some further refactoring to address that but it
made the resulting code significantly more complicated and, by my
judgement, harder to follow. Consequently I decided that a little
duplication was okay and warranted here because this logic is already
quite fiddly to read through and isn't likely to change significantly once
released (due to backward-compatibility promises).","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vdavalon01/terraform/commits/5a6d11e37533c7ca607a706a64fc6f1f079fdffa"},{"sha":"57d36c1d9da193448f58b35ce043ae55f71d9c82","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"addrs: ModuleInstance.ChildCall method

This allows us to concisely construct AbsModuleCall address values by
method chaining from module instance addresses.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vdavalon01/terraform/commits/57d36c1d9da193448f58b35ce043ae55f71d9c82"},{"sha":"51346f0d877633831d24d35283b4993375f01dd4","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"instances: Expander.AllInstances

In order to precisely implement the validation rules for "moved"
statements we need to be able to test whether particular instances were
declared in the configuration.

The instance expander is the source of record for which instances we
decided while creating a plan, but it's API is far more involved than what
our validation rules need, so this new AllInstances method returns a
wrapper object with a more straightforward API that provides read-only
access to just the question of whether particular instances got registered
in the expander already.

This API covers all three of the kinds of objects that move statements can
refer to. It includes module calls and resources, even though they aren't
_themselves_ "instances" in the sense we usually mean, because the module
instance addresses they are contained within _are_ instances and so we
need to take their dynamic instance keys into account when answering these
queries.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vdavalon01/terraform/commits/51346f0d877633831d24d35283b4993375f01dd4"},{"sha":"f76a3467dcfaab6fa7cc25c843ef92cfbf602fea","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"core: Call into refactoring.ValidateMoves after creating a plan

As of this commit, refactoring.ValidateMoves doesn't actually do anything
yet (always returns nil) but the goal here is to wire in the set of all
declared instances so that refactoring.ValidateMoves will then have all
of the information it needs to encapsulate our validation rules.

The actual implementation of refactoring.ValidateMoves will follow in
subsequent commits.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vdavalon01/terraform/commits/f76a3467dcfaab6fa7cc25c843ef92cfbf602fea"}]

Change-Id: I37d3a523696eba2f7d6da737ee3279991a074a56","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/6e3bc73e10b6f546876014b7d88e3690f16e440f"},{"sha":"ac72971cc6fbbfe4df7e67a8347ef1b6ab63b5fd","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[PJRT] Tweak the logic that orders the dimensions of A to handle degenerate minor dimensions better.

Improves transposes such as f32[1, 1024, 1]{2, 1, 0} -> f32[1, 1024, 1]{1, 2, 0}T(2, 128). Change-Id: I78371bae783f0f2422b15c02a4970f761a1e42ce","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sloppyjuicy/tensorflow/commits/fe96b2eface09e021726b502ca73ce02877fe5b4"},{"sha":"2c792ac08fa1e777d259a8da8a52382430e509f8","author":{"name":"George Karpenkov","email":"bbf3fb1cea1ba929a95f09c9e20513124012c8d3@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Serialize alias_passthrough_params property to HLO IR

Currently, the property is not serialized, which leads to inability to
reproduce bugs and performance regressions just from the IR, as the
alias_passthrough_params property affects the execution semantics.

The resulting modules are executable with run_hlo_module, but currently they
will miscompare against the reference implementation for the aliased params
(which still allows to compare other parameters, and check performance and

Change-Id: I2bf6a3db0a768fefeba76e824d53f2e06b373932","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sloppyjuicy/tensorflow/commits/c4b0364a37b36155673bc108ff56ed506ff96f1d"},{"sha":"36d30c8ed7fb0413c89b23c35c4ac1275ab93777","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Parse conv dnums with '?' when they appear in an HloModule.

conv dnums can contain '?', meaning, the N'th dimension doesn't have an
assigned value (it's not batch, feature, or a spatial dim).

Before this change, you could successfully parse a standalone conv dnums string
containing '?'.  What was broken was parsing such a string *in context*, as
part of a bigger HloModule.  This change fixes that.

[{"sha":"6397c035dac774b69689d0227b34752b71608ba0","author":{"name":"Daniel Ellis","email":"debc5fc5255503ceceb6184687cd26898e40e8ac@google.com"},"message":"Fix segmentation fault in shape inference logic.

When running shape functions, some functions (such as `MutableHashTableShape`)
produce extra output information in the form of a `ShapeAndType` struct.  The
shapes embedded in this struct are owned by an inference context that is
cleaned up almost immediately; if the upstream code attempts to access this
shape information, it can trigger a segfault.

`ShapeRefiner` is mitigating this for normal output shapes by cloning them
(and thus putting the newly created shape under ownership of an inference
context that will not die), but we were not doing the same for shapes and
types.  This commit fixes that by doing similar logic on output shapes and
types.

In fact, there was a pattern in dealing with mhlo.not. However, that operation included a mistake. It required the operand to be TF_IntOrFpTensor and it also demanded SameOperandsAndResultType. Under this circumstance, the pattern became a vacuous one as the result type of NotOp must be Bool and the input operand is IntOrFp. I fixed this bug by simply replacing TF_IntOrFpTensor with TF_BoolTensor in the definition of the pattern.

[{"sha":"528ebc948a58ac6353305f8345a50ab35717dbdb","author":{"name":"Daniel Ellis","email":"debc5fc5255503ceceb6184687cd26898e40e8ac@google.com"},"message":"Fix segmentation fault in shape inference logic.

When running shape functions, some functions (such as `MutableHashTableShape`)
produce extra output information in the form of a `ShapeAndType` struct.  The
shapes embedded in this struct are owned by an inference context that is
cleaned up almost immediately; if the upstream code attempts to access this
shape information, it can trigger a segfault.

`ShapeRefiner` is mitigating this for normal output shapes by cloning them
(and thus putting the newly created shape under ownership of an inference
context that will not die), but we were not doing the same for shapes and
types.  This commit fixes that by doing similar logic on output shapes and
types.

[{"sha":"604489d05f36647dd8815452ce22b295881f834b","author":{"name":"Peng Wang","email":"b55f18ff6423501a9509f40f9539fd4a14e4c9f9@google.com"},"message":"Removes the `SetIsStateful` mark on op `StatelessRandomGetKeyCounter` (the mark causes problems in tf.data iterator checkpointing).

Theoretically the op's output is device-dependent so it's kind of "stateful", but the V2 stateless RNG ops are also device-dependent (when alg=AUTO_SELECT) and not marked as stateful. We are using the same criterion here.

Note that removing the "stateful" mark won't cause the op to be constant-folded away (like `StatelessRandomGetAlg`).

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"[PJRT] Allow GPU memory oversubscription when unified memory is enabled.

With this CL, we can enable GPU memory oversubscription via env flags.
For example, `TF_FORCE_UNIFIED_MEMORY=1 XLA_PYTHON_CLIENT_MEM_FRACTION=8.0` provides 8x the GPU memory to the program. The 'extra' memory is physically located on the other GPU devices and the host's RAM, with swapping done transparently by CUDA.

With this CL, we can enable GPU memory oversubscription via env flags.
For example, `TF_FORCE_UNIFIED_MEMORY=1 XLA_PYTHON_CLIENT_MEM_FRACTION=8.0` provides 8x the GPU memory to the program. The 'extra' memory is physically located on the other GPU devices and the host's RAM, with swapping done transparently by CUDA.

This method encapsulates the move-processing rules for applying move
statements to ModuleInstance addresses. It honors both module call moves
and module instance moves by trying to find a subsequence of the input
that matches the "from" endpoint and then, if found, replacing it with
the "to" endpoint while preserving the prefix and suffix around the match,
if any.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/antoniomerlin/terraform/commits/4d733b4d2dc16cd5461905da06e00db95bb09698"},{"sha":"994ee23c06e21932cf9339c04d9ae3fabda0d26e","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"addrs: Module move support for AbsResource and AbsResourceInstance

This is a subset of the MoveDestination behavior for AbsResource and
AbsResourceInstance which deals with source and destination addresses that
refer to module calls or module instances.

They both work by delegating to ModuleInstance.MoveDestination and then
applying the same resource or resource instance address to the
newly-chosen module instance address, thus ensuring that when we move
a module we also move all of the resources inside that module in the same
way.

This doesn't yet include support for moving between specific resource or
resource instance addresses; that'll follow later. This commit should have
enough logic to support moving between module names and module instance
keys, including any module calls or resources nested within.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/antoniomerlin/terraform/commits/994ee23c06e21932cf9339c04d9ae3fabda0d26e"},{"sha":"fe77d732bed76c13a62b1d3d6568b0e4d1618c50","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #29251 from hashicorp/jbardin/issue-template

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Legalize mhlo.not to TFLogicalNotOp

In fact, there was a pattern in dealing with mhlo.not. However, that operation included a mistake. It required the operand to be TF_IntOrFpTensor and it also demanded SameOperandsAndResultType. Under this circumstance, the pattern became a vacuous one as the result type of NotOp must be Bool and the input operand is IntOrFp. I fixed this bug by simply replacing TF_IntOrFpTensor with TF_BoolTensor in the definition of the pattern.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Legalize mhlo.not to TFLogicalNotOp

In fact, there was a pattern in dealing with mhlo.not. However, that operation included a mistake. It required the operand to be TF_IntOrFpTensor and it also demanded SameOperandsAndResultType. Under this circumstance, the pattern became a vacuous one as the result type of NotOp must be Bool and the input operand is IntOrFp. I fixed this bug by simply replacing TF_IntOrFpTensor with TF_BoolTensor in the definition of the pattern.

[{"sha":"540ec49d54ee87680797727435d3bdca262b0f7a","author":{"name":"A. Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Legalize mhlo.not to TFLogicalNotOp

In fact, there was a pattern in dealing with mhlo.not. However, that operation included a mistake. It required the operand to be TF_IntOrFpTensor and it also demanded SameOperandsAndResultType. Under this circumstance, the pattern became a vacuous one as the result type of NotOp must be Bool and the input operand is IntOrFp. I fixed this bug by simply replacing TF_IntOrFpTensor with TF_BoolTensor in the definition of the pattern.

conv dnums can contain '?', meaning, the N'th dimension doesn't have an
assigned value (it's not batch, feature, or a spatial dim).

Before this change, you could successfully parse a standalone conv dnums string
containing '?'.  What was broken was parsing such a string *in context*, as
part of a bigger HloModule.  This change fixes that.

[{"sha":"604489d05f36647dd8815452ce22b295881f834b","author":{"name":"Peng Wang","email":"b55f18ff6423501a9509f40f9539fd4a14e4c9f9@google.com"},"message":"Removes the `SetIsStateful` mark on op `StatelessRandomGetKeyCounter` (the mark causes problems in tf.data iterator checkpointing).

Theoretically the op's output is device-dependent so it's kind of "stateful", but the V2 stateless RNG ops are also device-dependent (when alg=AUTO_SELECT) and not marked as stateful. We are using the same criterion here.

Note that removing the "stateful" mark won't cause the op to be constant-folded away (like `StatelessRandomGetAlg`).

Currently, the property is not serialized, which leads to inability to
reproduce bugs and performance regressions just from the IR, as the
alias_passthrough_params property affects the execution semantics.

The resulting modules are executable with run_hlo_module, but currently they
will miscompare against the reference implementation for the aliased params
(which still allows to compare other parameters, and check performance and
absence of crashes).

[{"sha":"57d36c1d9da193448f58b35ce043ae55f71d9c82","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"addrs: ModuleInstance.ChildCall method

This allows us to concisely construct AbsModuleCall address values by
method chaining from module instance addresses.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/57d36c1d9da193448f58b35ce043ae55f71d9c82"},{"sha":"51346f0d877633831d24d35283b4993375f01dd4","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"instances: Expander.AllInstances

In order to precisely implement the validation rules for "moved"
statements we need to be able to test whether particular instances were
declared in the configuration.

The instance expander is the source of record for which instances we
decided while creating a plan, but it's API is far more involved than what
our validation rules need, so this new AllInstances method returns a
wrapper object with a more straightforward API that provides read-only
access to just the question of whether particular instances got registered
in the expander already.

This API covers all three of the kinds of objects that move statements can
refer to. It includes module calls and resources, even though they aren't
_themselves_ "instances" in the sense we usually mean, because the module
instance addresses they are contained within _are_ instances and so we
need to take their dynamic instance keys into account when answering these
queries.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/51346f0d877633831d24d35283b4993375f01dd4"},{"sha":"f76a3467dcfaab6fa7cc25c843ef92cfbf602fea","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"core: Call into refactoring.ValidateMoves after creating a plan

As of this commit, refactoring.ValidateMoves doesn't actually do anything
yet (always returns nil) but the goal here is to wire in the set of all
declared instances so that refactoring.ValidateMoves will then have all
of the information it needs to encapsulate our validation rules.

The actual implementation of refactoring.ValidateMoves will follow in
subsequent commits.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/f76a3467dcfaab6fa7cc25c843ef92cfbf602fea"}]

[{"sha":"5e86bab15979c6d1ec1a73ac7b3137d9cccf1985","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"addrs: MoveDestination for AbsResource-based move endpoints

Previously our MoveDestination methods only honored move statements whose
endpoints were module calls or module instances.

Now we'll additionally handle when the endpoints are whole resource
addresses. This includes both renaming resource blocks and moving resource
blocks into or out of child modules.

This doesn't yet include endpoints that are specific resource _instances_,
which will follow in a subsequent commit. For the moment that situation
will always indicate a non-match.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/5e86bab15979c6d1ec1a73ac7b3137d9cccf1985"},{"sha":"45d16b4a2b6497b748127160f0bd15ed07a2e9cb","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"addrs: MoveDestination for AbsResourceInstance-based move endpoints

Previously our MoveDestination methods only honored move statements whose
endpoints were module calls, module instances, or resources.

Now we'll additionally handle when the endpoints are individual resource
instances. This situation only applies to
AbsResourceInstance.MoveDestination because no other objects can be
contained inside of a resource instance.

This completes all of the MoveDestination cases for all supported move
statement types and moveable object types.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/45d16b4a2b6497b748127160f0bd15ed07a2e9cb"},{"sha":"5a6d11e37533c7ca607a706a64fc6f1f079fdffa","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"addrs: Factor out MoveEndpointInModule module prefix matching

All of our MoveDestination methods have the common problem of deciding
whether the receiver is even potentially in the scope of a particular
MoveEndpointInModule, which requires that the receiver belong to an
instance of the module where the move statement was found.

Previously we had this logic inline in all three cases, but now we'll
factor it out into a shared helper function.

At first it seemed like there ought to be more factoring possible for
the AbsResource vs. AbsResourceInstance implementations, since textually
they look very similar, but in practice they only look similar because
those two types have a lot of method names in common, but the Go compiler
sees them as completely distinct and thus we must write the same logic
out twice. I did try some further refactoring to address that but it
made the resulting code significantly more complicated and, by my
judgement, harder to follow. Consequently I decided that a little
duplication was okay and warranted here because this logic is already
quite fiddly to read through and isn't likely to change significantly once
released (due to backward-compatibility promises).","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/5a6d11e37533c7ca607a706a64fc6f1f079fdffa"}]

PiperOrigin-RevId: 387386114
Change-Id: I78371bae783f0f2422b15c02a4970f761a1e42ce","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/fe96b2eface09e021726b502ca73ce02877fe5b4"},{"sha":"2c792ac08fa1e777d259a8da8a52382430e509f8","author":{"name":"George Karpenkov","email":"bbf3fb1cea1ba929a95f09c9e20513124012c8d3@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Serialize alias_passthrough_params property to HLO IR

Currently, the property is not serialized, which leads to inability to
reproduce bugs and performance regressions just from the IR, as the
alias_passthrough_params property affects the execution semantics.

The resulting modules are executable with run_hlo_module, but currently they
will miscompare against the reference implementation for the aliased params
(which still allows to compare other parameters, and check performance and
absence of crashes).
